</script>

Everything you've learned applies off-screen too. A poster, flyer, business card—these are just UI on paper. Hierarchy, spacing, typography, and color restraint all transfer directly. But print has its own quirks.

## What Changes on Paper (Besides the Smell)

- **Resolution is fixed but very high.** Screens are 72–144 PPI. Print is 300+ PPI. Your subtle 1px borders might disappear. Your fine details can finally shine.
- **Color mode shifts.** Screens use RGB (light). Printers use CMYK (ink). Saturated screen colors look dull in print. Blues go purple. Neons go muddy.
- **No interactivity.** No hover states. No scrolling. Everything must be visible at once, at one scale.
- **Physical size matters.** A business card read at arm's length is different from a billboard read at 100 feet. The same type size means completely different things.

## Applying Your UI Principles (The Greatest Hits)

- **Hierarchy still rules.** A poster needs exactly one dominant element: the headline, the date or the image. Everything else is secondary. The “squint test” works here too.
- **Whitespace is still power.** A poster with too much content looks cheap. Restraint signals quality. The Economist’s magazine covers are legendary precisely because they use so little.
- **Alignment is even more visible on paper.** When you’re holding a flyer, misalignment is glaring. Use a grid. Align everything to it. No exceptions.
- **Typography contrast matters more.** At print scale, text smaller than 8pt becomes illegible. Body text should be 10–12pt minimum. Hierarchy needs larger jumps, a headline at 14pt and body at 12pt is not enough contrast.

## The Print Hierarchy Scale (For the Real World)

```
Billboard    → 10"+ headline size
Poster A1    → 2–4" headline, 0.5" subline
Flyer A5     → 36–48pt headline, 10–12pt body
Business card → 11pt name, 8pt title
```

## Rules

- Print hierarchy needs larger jumps than screen hierarchy.
- Convert RGB to CMYK before printing. Test on your printer first.
- Any element touching the page edge needs 0.125" (3mm) bleed area.
- Use CMYK black for text: C:0 M:0 Y:0 K:100, not RGB(0,0,0).
- Whitespace on printed pieces is expensive. Use it deliberately.

