The cluttered version tries to say everything. The focused version makes one decision: the headline is the hook. Everything else supports it. The viewer knows instantly what this is.

## Quick Exercise

Find a physical flyer or poster (yours or someone else's). Squint at it. Can you still read the most important information blurred? If not, something's competing with the headline and needs to be removed or shrunk.

## Simple Formula

```
ONE visual hook      → dominant headline or image
TWO facts           → when + where
ONE action          → register / call / visit
minimal brand       → small logo or URL at bottom
```

Everything beyond this is clutter unless you have a reason.

## Quick Recap

- Print follows the same hierarchy and spacing rules as screen.
- Different constraints: fixed size, no interactivity, RGB → CMYK, larger type needed.
- More whitespace signals quality on paper.
- One dominant element. Two facts. One action.
